@node Tutorials
@chapter Tutorials

@cindex tutorials
@cindex walkthrough
@cindex hello world

This chapter provides step-by-step walkthroughs of common tasks.

@strong{Note}: some workflows are affected by known bugs in v1.6.1.
The compile cycle (F9) may crash when parsing compiler error messages.
These tutorials will be updated once the bugs are fixed.  The steps
described are architecturally correct and represent how xwpe is
designed to work.

@section Tutorial 1: Hello World in C

@subsection Goal
Create, compile, and run a simple C program entirely within xwpe.

@subsection Steps

@enumerate
@item
Start xwpe in programming mode:
@example
wpe
@end example

@item
Create a new file: @kbd{Alt-F N}.  A new buffer named ``Noname'' opens.

@item
Type the program:
@example
#include <stdio.h>

int main() @{
    printf("Hello, world!\n");
    return 0;
@}
@end example

@item
Save the file: @kbd{Alt-F A} (Save As), type @code{hello.c}, press
@key{Return}.

@item
Compile: press @key{F9} (Make).  xwpe invokes @code{gcc -c -o hello.o
hello.c} and then links the executable.  If there are errors, they
appear in the Message Window; press @kbd{Alt-R N} to jump to each
error.

@item
Run: press @kbd{Ctrl-F9} (Run).  The program executes and
``Hello, world!'' appears in the output.

@item
Quit: press @kbd{Ctrl-Q}.
@end enumerate

@section Tutorial 2: Multi-file project

@subsection Goal
Create a project with two source files and a shared header.

@subsection Steps

@enumerate
@item
Create three files:

@file{main.c}:
@example
#include <stdio.h>
#include "utils.h"

int main() @{
    printf("Sum: %d\n", add(3, 4));
    return 0;
@}
@end example

@file{utils.h}:
@example
int add(int a, int b);
@end example

@file{utils.c}:
@example
#include "utils.h"

int add(int a, int b) @{
    return a + b;
@}
@end example

@item
Open a project: @kbd{Alt-P P}, type @code{myproject}, press
@key{Return}.

@item
Configure the project in the options dialog:
@itemize @bullet
@item Compiler: @code{/usr/bin/gcc}
@item Compiler Options: @code{-Wall -g}
@item Executable Name: @code{myprogram}
@end itemize

@item
Add files to the project: @kbd{Alt-P A}, add @code{main.c} and
@code{utils.c}.

@item
Build: press @key{F9}.  xwpe compiles both files and links them
into @code{myprogram}.

@item
Run: press @kbd{Ctrl-F9}.  Output: @code{Sum: 7}.
@end enumerate

@section Tutorial 3: Debugging a segfault

@subsection Goal
Use the integrated debugger to find and fix a null pointer dereference.

@subsection Steps

@enumerate
@item
Create @file{buggy.c}:
@example
#include <stdio.h>

int factorial(int n) @{
    if (n <= 1) return 1;
    return n * factorial(n - 1);
@}

int main() @{
    int x = 5;
    int result = factorial(x);
    printf("factorial(%d) = %d\n", x, result);

    int *ptr = NULL;
    *ptr = 42;  /* deliberate crash */

    return 0;
@}
@end example

@item
Compile with debug symbols: set Compiler Options to @code{-g -O0},
then press @key{F9}.

@item
Start the debugger: press @kbd{Ctrl-F10}.

@item
Set a breakpoint at @code{int x = 5;}: move the cursor there and
press @kbd{Ctrl-F8}.

@item
Continue: press @kbd{Ctrl-F10}.  The program stops at the breakpoint.

@item
Add a watch: press @kbd{Ctrl-F7}, type @code{x}, press @key{Return}.
The Watch Window shows the value of @code{x}.

@item
Step through: press @key{F8} repeatedly.  Watch @code{x} and
@code{result} change as the program executes.

@item
When the program reaches @code{*ptr = 42;}, it will crash with
SIGSEGV.  gdb catches the signal and xwpe shows the offending line.

@item
View the stack: press @kbd{Ctrl-F6} to see that the crash occurred
in @code{main()} at the null pointer dereference.

@item
Fix the bug: remove or comment out the @code{*ptr = 42;} line.
Recompile with @key{F9} and run with @kbd{Ctrl-F9}.

@item
Quit the debugger: press @kbd{Ctrl-F2}.
@end enumerate
